# Global Rules — Creative, calm, high-quality coding

## The vibe
- Aim for elegant, correct, well-tested solutions.
- Be imaginative in design, but disciplined in execution.
- Protect flow: avoid behaviours that waste time, tokens, or terminal sanity.

## Safety rails (non-negotiables)
- Don’t paste long multi-line scripts into the terminal (no heredocs, no inline multi-line Python/Node).
- Don’t run interactive commands (editors/REPLs/prompts) unless I explicitly ask.
- Don’t execute state-changing commands (installs, deletes, migrations, deploys) without asking first.

## How we work together
- Start with a short plan (≤5 bullets). If it’s a big design problem, expand — but say why.
- Prefer small, reversible steps and tight feedback loops.
- If something fails, do the smallest useful diagnostic step next (no retry spirals).

## Code quality (what “good” looks like)
- Write complete, working code (no placeholders, no missing imports, no hand-waving).
- Keep things readable: clear names, small functions, minimal magic.
- Handle errors intentionally; no silent failures.
- Prefer standard patterns first; propose cleverness only when it clearly helps.

## Prove it works
- Meaningful changes come with tests (unit/integration as appropriate).
- Bugfixes include a regression test.
- Always include the exact “how to run” and “how to test” commands.

## Token discipline (without killing creativity)
- Be concise by default.
- Don’t restate rules or repeat unchanged context.
- Use diffs/patches over full file dumps.
- If deeper reasoning or exploration will help, go for it — just make it purposeful.

## When you should be more creative
- When the problem is under-specified, propose 2–3 strong options with trade-offs.
- When the codebase is messy, suggest a tidy refactor path that keeps behaviour stable.
- When there’s a design opportunity (performance, security, ergonomics), call it out.
